Responses to infectious disease epidemics use a growing body of data sources to inform decision making ( 
 Cori 
  et al., 2017
 ; 
 Fraser 
  et al., 2009
 ; 
 WHO Ebola Response Team 
  et al., 2014
 ; 
 WHO Ebola Response Team 
  et al., 2015
 ). While new data—such as whole genome pathogen sequences—are increasingly useful complements to epidemiological data ( 
 Gire 
  et al., 2014
 ), epidemic curves—which describe the number of new cases through time (incidence)—remain the most important source of information, particularly early in an outbreak. Specifically epidemic curves(often referred to as ‘epicurves’) represent the number of new cases per time unit based on the date or time of symptom onset.
